SELECTION SORT IS ONE OF THE SIMPLEST SORTING ALGORITHMS

HOW IT WORKS
Step 1: Assume the first element of the unsorted part is the smallest (we store its index).

Step 2: Compare this "assumed smallest" with every other element in the remaining unsorted part.

Step 3: If a smaller element is found, update your "smallest index" to point to this new value.

Step 4: Once you reach the end of the unsorted part, swap the element at the "smallest index" with the first element of the unsorted part.

Step 5: Repeat the process for the next position until the entire array is sorted.






Input Array:
[64, 25, 12, 22, 11]

Pass 1: Finding the Smallest
- Compare [64, 25] → 25 is smaller
- Compare [25, 12] → 12 is smaller
- Compare [12, 22] → 12 is smaller
- Compare [12, 11] → 11 is smaller
- Swap 64 ↔ 11
Result: [11, 25, 12, 22, 64]

Pass 2: Next Smallest
- Compare [25, 12] → 12 is smaller
- Compare [12, 22] → 12 is smaller
- Compare [12, 64] → 12 is smaller
- Swap 25 ↔ 12
Result: [11, 12, 25, 22, 64]

Pass 3: Next Smallest
- Compare [25, 22] → 22 is smaller
- Compare [22, 64] → 22 is smaller
- Swap 25 ↔ 22
Result: [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]

Pass 4: Next Smallest
- Compare [25, 64] → 25 is smaller
- No swap needed
Result: [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]

Pass 5: Last element already in place
Final Sorted Array: [11, 12, 22, 25, 64]

--------------------------------------------







Case,Time Complexity,When does this happen?
Best     Case,O(N^2),Even if array is sorted, selection sort still scans entire array.
Average  Case,O(N^2),Array is in random order.
Worst    Case,O(N^2),Array is sorted in reverse order.
Space Complexity,O(1),"No extra space needed; it sorts ""in-place."""

Stable? No (it may change the relative order of equal elements).
In-place? Yes (it doesn't need extra memory).
Use Case? Good for small datasets or when memory is extremely limited.
